{"title_page": "Bicycle counter", "text_new": "[[File:Cycle counter.jpg|thumb|440x440px|Bicycle counter in [[Copenhagen]].]]\n'''Bicycle counters''' are [[Electronics|electronic devices]] that detect the number of [[Bicycle|bicycles]] at a location for a certain period of time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/energy/intelligent/projects/sites/iee-projects/files/projects/documents/presto_fact_sheet_bicycle_baromoters_en.pdf|title=Bicycle barometers (bike counters)|last=European Commission|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They are sometimes referred to as '''bicycle barometers''',<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://peopleforbikes.org/blog/the-magic-of-bike-barometers/|title=The magic of bike barometers|last=Brooks|first=Karen|date=2014-09-22|website=PeopleForBikes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> but the term is misleading because it indicates the [[Barometer|measurement of pressure]]. Most counting stations only consist of a sensor (and the internal computing device) and some use a display to show the total number of cyclists of the day and the current year<ref name=\":0\" />. There are counting stations all over the world in over hundreds of cities,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eco-compteur.com/en/products/|title=Products|website=Eco-Counter|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> for example in [[Odense]],<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Zagreb]], or in [[Hawthorne Bridge bicycle counter|Portland]]. The first bicycle counting station was installed in Odense, Denmark, in 2002.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Technical Setup ==\n[[File:Bicycle counter.jpg|thumb|A bicycle counter in [[Mannheim]] with pneumatic hoses to detect the number of cyclists.]]\n[[File:Ab\u00e1dszal\u00f3k (Tiszaderzsi szivatty\u00fatelep) Tiszamenti ker\u00e9kp\u00e1r\u00fat (EuroVelo-11) Kisk\u00f6re fel\u00e9 2018-09-09.JPG|thumb|Narrowed passage at the Tisza Cycleway in Hungary with cameras to count cyclists.]]\n[[File:BikePedCounterSetup 2008.gif|thumb|The technical equpment of a bicycle counter next to a cycle path, using an infrared sensor.]]\nDifferent techniques are used for detection of bicycles, such as built in [[Induction loop|induction loops]], [[Pneumatics|pneumatic]] hoses, [[infrared]] sensing<ref name=\":2\" /> or cameras.\n\n== Features ==\nBicycle counting stations are said to raise awareness for cycling as a mode of transportation, provide the data for monitoring bicycle usage and encourage more people to use their bicycles and give cyclists acknowledgement.\n\nBicycle counting stations can be described as persuasive technology.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Claes|first=Sandy|last2=Slegers|first2=Karin|last3=Vande Moere|first3=Andrew|date=2016-05-07|title=The Bicycle Barometer: Design and Evaluation of Cyclist-Specific Interaction for a Public Display|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/2858036.2858429|journal=Proceedings of the 2016 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems|language=en|location=San Jose California USA|publisher=ACM|pages=5824\u20135835|doi=10.1145/2858036.2858429|isbn=978-1-4503-3362-7}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\"Through sensing technology, a display can act as a tool that increases the capability to capture a behavior (e.g., measuring residential energy consumption, bicycle use, etc.); through its visual imagery, it can function as a medium that provides useful information, such as behavioral statistics or cause-and-effect relationships; and through its networking ability, it can become a social actor, encouraging community-based feedback and social interaction\".<ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>\n\nUnlike other bicycle related interventions or [[citizen science]], where citizens manually put in data,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Claes|first=Sandy|last2=Slegers|first2=Karin|last3=Vande Moere|first3=Andrew|date=2016-05-07|title=The Bicycle Barometer: Design and Evaluation of Cyclist-Specific Interaction for a Public Display|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/2858036.2858429|journal=Proceedings of the 2016 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems|language=en|location=San Jose California USA|publisher=ACM|pages=5824\u20135835|doi=10.1145/2858036.2858429|isbn=978-1-4503-3362-7}}</ref> bicycle counting stations automatically generate citizen related data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eco-compteur.com/en/home/|title=Home - Automated pedestrian & bicycle counters|website=Eco-Counter|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThey fulfill certain criteria of [[Ambient intelligence]], such as being [[Embedded system|embedded,]] [[Context awareness|context-aware]] and [[Adaptive behavior|adaptive]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pousman|first=Zachary|last2=Stasko|first2=John|date=2006|title=A taxonomy of ambient information systems: four patterns of design|url=http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=1133265.1133277|journal=Proceedings of the working conference on Advanced visual interfaces  - AVI '06|language=en|location=Venezia, Italy|publisher=ACM Press|pages=67|doi=10.1145/1133265.1133277|isbn=978-1-59593-353-9}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\nCycling barometer is also the name of a ranking by the [[European Cyclists' Federation]] for the most bicycle-friendly nations in the [[European Union|EU]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecf.com/resources/cycling-facts-and-figures/ecf-cycling-barometer|title=ECF Cycling barometer {{!}} ECF|website=ecf.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>.\n\nThere has been creative use of the data generated by counting stations, such as an [[Information design|information-design]] poster which includes number of daily [[Cycling|cyclists]], [[precipitation]] and [[temperature]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasteinplace.com/Bicycle-Barometer|title=Bicycle Barometer - Paste in Place|website=www.pasteinplace.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{commons|Category:Bicycle counters}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cycling]]\n[[Category:Road traffic management]]\n[[Category:Transportation planning]]\n[[Category:Road transport]]\n[[Category:Counting instruments]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Cycle counter.jpg|thumb|440x440px|Bicycle counter in [[Copenhagen]].]]\n'''Bicycle counters''' are [[Electronics|electronic devices]] that detect the number of [[Bicycle|bicycles]] at a location for a certain period of time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/energy/intelligent/projects/sites/iee-projects/files/projects/documents/presto_fact_sheet_bicycle_baromoters_en.pdf|title=Bicycle barometers (bike counters)|last=European Commission|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They are sometimes referred to as '''bicycle barometers''',<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://peopleforbikes.org/blog/the-magic-of-bike-barometers/|title=The magic of bike barometers|last=Brooks|first=Karen|date=2014-09-22|website=PeopleForBikes|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> but the term is misleading because it indicates the [[Barometer|measurement of pressure]]. Most counting stations only consist of a sensor (and the internal computing device) and some use a display to show the total number of cyclists of the day and the current year<ref name=\":0\" />. There are counting stations all over the world in over hundreds of cities,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eco-compteur.com/en/products/|title=Products|website=Eco-Counter|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> for example in [[Odense]],<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Zagreb]], or in [[Hawthorne Bridge bicycle counter|Portland]]. The first bicycle counting station was installed in Odense, Denmark, in 2002.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Technical Setup ==\n[[File:Bicycle counter.jpg|thumb|A bicycle counter in [[Mannheim]] with pneumatic hoses to detect the number of cyclists.]]\n[[File:Ab\u00e1dszal\u00f3k (Tiszaderzsi szivatty\u00fatelep) Tiszamenti ker\u00e9kp\u00e1r\u00fat (EuroVelo-11) Kisk\u00f6re fel\u00e9 2018-09-09.JPG|thumb|Narrowed passage at the Tisza Cycleway in Hungary with cameras to count cyclists.]]\n[[File:BikePedCounterSetup 2008.gif|thumb|The technical equpment of a bicycle counter next to a cycle path, using an infrared sensor.]]\nDifferent techniques are used for detection of bicycles, such as built in [[Induction loop|induction loops]], [[Pneumatics|pneumatic]] hoses, [[infrared]] sensing<ref name=\":2\" /> or cameras.\n\n== Features ==\nBicycle counting stations are said to raise awareness for cycling as a mode of transportation, provide the data for monitoring bicycle usage and encourage more people to use their bicycles and give cyclists acknowledgement.\n\nBicycle counting stations can be described as persuasive technology.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Claes|first=Sandy|last2=Slegers|first2=Karin|last3=Vande Moere|first3=Andrew|date=2016-05-07|title=The Bicycle Barometer: Design and Evaluation of Cyclist-Specific Interaction for a Public Display|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/2858036.2858429|journal=Proceedings of the 2016 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems|language=en|location=San Jose California USA|publisher=ACM|pages=5824\u20135835|doi=10.1145/2858036.2858429|isbn=978-1-4503-3362-7}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\"Through sensing technology, a display can act as a tool that increases the capability to capture a behavior (e.g., measuring residential energy consumption, bicycle use, etc.); through its visual imagery, it can function as a medium that provides useful information, such as behavioral statistics or cause-and-effect relationships; and through its networking ability, it can become a social actor, encouraging community-based feedback and social interaction\".<ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>\n\nUnlike other bicycle related interventions or [[citizen science]], where citizens manually put in data,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Claes|first=Sandy|last2=Slegers|first2=Karin|last3=Vande Moere|first3=Andrew|date=2016-05-07|title=The Bicycle Barometer: Design and Evaluation of Cyclist-Specific Interaction for a Public Display|url=https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/2858036.2858429|journal=Proceedings of the 2016 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems|language=en|location=San Jose California USA|publisher=ACM|pages=5824\u20135835|doi=10.1145/2858036.2858429|isbn=978-1-4503-3362-7}}</ref> bicycle counting stations automatically generate citizen related data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eco-compteur.com/en/home/|title=Home - Automated pedestrian & bicycle counters|website=Eco-Counter|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThey fulfill certain criteria of [[Ambient intelligence]], such as being [[Embedded system|embedded,]] [[Context awareness|context-aware]] and [[Adaptive behavior|adaptive]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pousman|first=Zachary|last2=Stasko|first2=John|date=2006|title=A taxonomy of ambient information systems: four patterns of design|url=http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=1133265.1133277|journal=Proceedings of the working conference on Advanced visual interfaces  - AVI '06|language=en|location=Venezia, Italy|publisher=ACM Press|pages=67|doi=10.1145/1133265.1133277|isbn=978-1-59593-353-9}}</ref>\n\n== Trivia ==\nCycling barometer is also the name of a ranking by the [[European Cyclists' Federation]] for the most bicycle-friendly nations in the [[European Union|EU]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecf.com/resources/cycling-facts-and-figures/ecf-cycling-barometer|title=ECF Cycling barometer {{!}} ECF|website=ecf.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>.\n\nThere has been creative use of the data generated by counting stations, such as an [[Information design|information-design]] poster which includes number of daily [[Cycling|cyclists]], [[precipitation]] and [[temperature]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pasteinplace.com/Bicycle-Barometer|title=Bicycle Barometer - Paste in Place|website=www.pasteinplace.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{commons|Category:Bicycle counters}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cycling]]\n[[Category:Road traffic management]]\n[[Category:Transportation planning]]\n[[Category:Road transport]]\n[[Category:Counting instruments]]\n", "name_user": "Schlawensko", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrivia:changed the title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicycle_counter"}
